<TEXT>
<P>
The PBS documentary "When We Were Young: Growing Up on the Silver Screen" might 
have been interesting and informative had it not been for the stupid and 
ridiculous narration. It was so insulting to the intelligence that I could 
stand only about 45 minutes of it. Anyone who lived through the era would know 
all about the material Maureen Stapleton was given to read. Compare that to the 
Richard Burton programs or the series on Hollywood that James Mason did. These 
were programs with substance that were filled with fascinating and little-known 
material. 
</P>
<P>
Art Merrill, San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
